{"id": "river_paraphrase", "obfuscation_class": "paraphrase", "clean": "The river moved slowly under the bridge. Children laughed near the bank, throwing small stones that skipped across the dark water. An old man watched from a bench, his hands folded, his coat buttoned against the wind. He remembered other afternoons, other rivers, other children whose names he had long since forgotten. The light fell sideways through the trees and the whole scene looked, for a moment, like a painting nobody had bothered to finish. A dog barked twice and then was quiet. The man stood, brushed his coat, and walked toward the town where the lamps were already coming on.", "obfuscated": "Below the bridge the current drifted along without hurry. By the water's edge kids were laughing and tossing pebbles that bounced over the dark surface. From a bench an elderly man looked on, coat done up against the breeze, his hands clasped in his lap. He thought of past afternoons, of rivers he had known, of youngsters whose names time had taken from him. Slanting light came through the branches, and briefly the place resembled an unfinished canvas. Somewhere a dog barked, then fell silent. The man rose, smoothed his coat, and set off for the town, where the streetlamps were beginning to glow."}
